[[File:Illustration of Allied countries strangling Hideki Tojo.jpg|thumbnail|Illustration of [[Allied forces (World War II)|Allied countries]] strangling [[Hideki Tojo]]. Flags representing [[Great Britain]], [[Republic of China]], the Japanese People's Emancipation League, and the [[United States]] are pictured on the sleeves of each hand. ]]
The '''Japanese People's Emancipation League''' (Japanese: Nihon Jinmin Kaiho Renmei)<ref name="United States. Congress. Senate. Committee on the Judiciary 1956 3502–3505">{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/stream/scopeofsovietact5054unit#page/3502/mode/2up| title=Scope of Soviet activity in the United States.  | publisher= United States. Congress. Senate. Committee on the Judiciary.| volume=Parts 50-54| author= United States. Congress. Senate. Committee on the Judiciary|year=1956| pages=3502–3505| isbn=}}</ref> or '''Emancipation League''', was a Japanese resistance organization that operated in [[Communist China (1931-1937)|communist China]] during the [[Second Sino-Japanese War]], and [[World War II]].<ref name="roth">Roth, Andrew (1945). Dilemma in Japan. Little, Brown. pp. 162-188</ref>

==History==
In 1944, the Japanese People's Emancipation League was established in [[Yan'an]].<ref name="roth"/> The Emancipation League had a three-point program: "opposition to the war, the overthrow of the militarists, and the establishment of a democratic, people's government in postwar Japan".<ref name="roth"/> It was estimated that the Japanese People's Emancipation League had numbered more than 300<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=t0EEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA42&lpg=PA42 ''Life'' December 18, 1944]</ref> to 450 members.<ref name="United States. Congress. Senate. Committee on the Judiciary 1956 3502–3505"/>

==Banner==
The Japanese People's Emancipation League had a banner.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://collections.lib.uwm.edu/cdm/ref/collection/agsphoto/id/18998|title= Yanan (China), banners for school and Japanese People's Emancipation League|publisher= [[University of Wisconsin–Milwaukee]]|date=1944}}</ref>

